xes

Class Event

  • java.lang.Object
    • xes.Event

  • public class Event
extends java.lang.Object
    This class contains all the attributes of the events retrieved from Apache ODE's internal MySQL database and the methods required for reading the events, retrieving event string data, filtering events and checking for events that contain new instances.

    The eventID represents the event id retrieved from the database. It is of int data type and is used to identify a certain event.

    The eventDetails represents the detail string retrieved from the database and contains various details of the event, such as the Activity Id, Activity Type, Declaration Id and others.

    The scopeId represents the scope id retrieved from the database. It is of int data type and is used to identify a certain scope. A scope is a BPEL element that allows partners, process data or handlers to be declared locally.

    The timestamp represents the timestamp retrieved from the database and is of Timestamp data type. It represents the date and time at which the event happened.

    The eventType represents the type of the event retrieved from the database. It is of String data type and consists of various states such as enabled, started, modified, ended of the process instances, activities, scopes or variables.

    The instanceId represents the id of an instance retrieved from the database. It is of int data type and is used to identify instances.

    The ActivityName represents the name of the activity occurred in the current event. It is of String data type and can have various values related to the process.

    The eventLifecycle represents the life cycle state of the event. It is of String data type and the filtered events can have the "started" or "ended" state.

    The messageId represents the message exchange id of a process instance. It is of String data type and consists of a mix of letters and digits. This is used in the application to retrieve the instance input variables from the ODE_MESSAGE table as it is the only common variable of the two tables.

    Specific to the ATM Withdrawal process!

    As this is an ATM Withdrawal process, the user needs to enter the pin and the requested amount. The inputPin and inputAmount represent the input variables for an instance of the process and they are being traced in the event log in order to improve the upcoming predictions.

    The processName represents the name of the process retrieved from the database. It is of String data type and is used to identify processes.

      • readProcessInput

        public static void readProcessInput(java.sql.ResultSet resultSet)
                             throws java.sql.SQLException
        Reads the values of the Pin and Amount variables entered by the user. This is being accomplished by searching for the first appearance of the strings "PIN" and "Amount" in the messageData retrieved from the messageDataSet. Then, the messageData string is parsed until the inputPin and inputAmount were obtained.

        Specific to the ATM Withdrawal process!

        Parameters:
        resultSet - the result set being used
        Throws:
        java.sql.SQLException - if data cannot be retrieved from result set

      • eventFilter

        public static boolean eventFilter()
        Filters the events based on 3 conditions.The first one is the event should have an activity name in the retrieved eventDetails string. The second one is the eventType should not have the state "Enabled". The third condition filters the events related to "Assign" activities of the process.

        By doing so, all the remaining events have an activity name, they have the "Started" or "Ended" state and are not related to the numerous "Assign" activities.

        Returns:
        boolean
